ise Calder\n| Episode: \"Snow in Provence\"\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Absolutely Fabulous]]''\n| Art Gallery Assistant\n| Episode: \"Death\"\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Minder (TV series)|Minder]]''\n| Vanessa\n| Episode: \"All Quiet on the West End Front\"\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Cadfael]]''\n| Cecily Corde\n| Episode: \"The Sanctuary Sparrow\"\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''{{sortname|A|Breed of Heroes|nolink=1}}''\n| Janet\n| Television film\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Karaoke (TV series)|Karaoke]]''\n| Angie\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Cold Lazarus]]''\n| Angie\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''{{sortname|The|Other Boleyn Girl|The Other Boleyn Girl (2003 film)}}''\n| [[Mary Boleyn]]\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Revelations (TV miniseries)|Revelations]]''\n| Sister Josepha Montafiore\n| Miniseries\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''{{sortname|The|Company|The Company (TV miniseries)}}''\n| Elizabet Nemeth\n| Miniseries\n|-\n| 2007\u20132014\n| ''[[Californication (TV series)|Californication]]''\n| Karen\n| 84 episodes\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''10 Minute Tales''\n| Woman\n| Television short; segment: \"Deep & Crisp & Even\"\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Thorne (TV series)|Thorne: Sleepyhead]]''\n| Anne Coburn\n| Episodes 1-3\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Saints & Strangers]]''\n| Elizabeth Hopkins\n| Miniseries\n|-\n| 2016\u20132017\n| ''[[Designated Survivor (TV series)|Designated Survivor]]''\n| First Lady Alex Kirkman\n| Series regular (Season 1 and 2)\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[The First (TV series)|The First]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/09/natascha-mcelhone-cast-beau-willimon-the-first-hulu-exit-designated-survivor-abc-1202177797/|title=Natascha McElhone To Star In Beau Willimon\u2019s \u2018The First\u2019 Hulu Series, Will Depart \u2018Designated Survivor\u2019|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=27 September 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n| Laz Ingram\n| Series regular\n|-\n| 2021\n| ''[[Halo (franchise) #Showtime television series|Halo]]''\n| [[Catherine Halsey|Dr. Catherine Halsey]]<hr>[[Cortana (Halo)|Cortana]]\n| Series regular<ref>https://deadline.com/2019/08/halo-natascha-mcelhone-bokeem-woodbine-cast-showtime-series-based-xbox-franchise-1202659705/</ref>\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|+ List of video game appearances\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Castlevania: Lords of Shadow]]''<ref name=\"cv\" />\n| Marie Belmont\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Castlevania: Lords of Shadow 2]]''\n| Marie Belmont\n|\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n|+ Awards and nominations\n|-\n! Year\n! Nominated work\n! Award\n! Category\n! Result\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Ronin (film)|Ronin]]'' \n| [[MTV Movie Awards]]\n| Best Action Sequence (shared with [[Robert De Niro]])\n| {{Nominated}}<ref name=\"Awards\">{{cite web|title=Awards for Natascha McElhone|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0001523/awards|publisher=Internet Movie Database|accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n| 2003\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''[[Solaris (2002 film)|Solaris]]''\n| [[Saturn Award]]\n| Best Actress\n| {{Nominated}}<ref name=\"Awards\"/> \n|-\n| 2003\n| [[Irish Film and Television Awards]]\n| Best Actress in Film\n| {{Nominated}}<ref name=\"Awards\"/> \n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Revelations (2005 TV series)|Revelations]]''\n| [[Satellite Award]]\n| Outstanding Actress in a Miniseries or a Motion Picture Made for Television\n| {{Nominated}}<ref name=\"Awards\"/> \n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Natascha McElhone}}\n* {{IMDb name|1523}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McElhone, Natascha}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Surrey]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London Academy of Music and Dramatic Art]]\n[[Category:English memoirists]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:English film actresses]]\n[[Category:English stage actresses]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British Shakespearean actresses]]\n[[Category:English voice actresses]]\n[[Category:English video game actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Natascha McElhone\n| image              = Natascha McElhone May 2018.jpg\n| caption            = McElhone in May 2018\n| birth_name         = Natasha Abigail Taylor\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1969|12|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Walton-on-Thames]], [[Surrey]], England\n| alma_mater         = [[London Academy of Music and Dramatic Art]]\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 1990\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{Marriage|Martin Hirigoyen Kelly|1998|2008|end=died}}\n| parents            = Noreen McElhone <br /> Michael Taylor <br />[[Roy Greenslade]] {{small|(stepfather)}}\n| children           = 3\n| nationality        = British, Irish\n}}\n\n'''Natasha Abigail Taylor''' (born 14 December 1969),<ref>{{cite news |title=Natascha McElhone|url=https://www.empireonline.com/people/natascha-mcelhone/ |accessdate=13 April 2020 |magazine=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]}}</ref> known professionally as '''Natascha McElhone''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|m|\u00e6|k|\u0259l|h|o\u028a|n}}), is an English actress. \n\nIn film, she is best known for her roles in ''[[Ronin_(film)|Ronin]]'' (1998), ''[[The Truman Show]]'' (1998) and ''[[Solaris (2002 film)|Solaris]]'' (2002). On television, she has portrayed Karen van der Beek, the long-time partner of [[Hank Moody]], in the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] comedy-drama series ''[[Californication (TV series)|Californication]]'' (2007\u20132014), [[First Lady]] Alex Kirkman in the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] political drama ''[[Designated Survivor (TV series)|Designated Survivor]]''<ref name=\"deadline.com\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/kal-penn-maggie-q-natascha-mcelhone-italia-ricci-cast-designated-survivor-abc-1201696876/ |title='Designated Survivor' Casts Kal Penn, Maggie Q, Natascha McElhone, Italia Ricci |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=5 February 2016 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref> (2016\u20132017), and Laz Ingram in [[Beau Willimon]]'s [[Hulu]] science-fiction series ''[[The First (TV series)|The First]]'' (2018).\n\n==Early life==\nShe was born Natasha Abigail Taylor in Walton-on-Thames, [[Surrey]] in 1969<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=QKFsU3NCb%2FgZwY1%2BPlzSWA&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=25 February 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref><ref name=\"it2009\">{{cite news | date = 10 October 2009 | author = Gr\u00e1inne Faller | url = http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/magazine/2009/1010/1224256064873.html | title = Shot In The Arm | newspaper = [[Irish Times]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180822163834/https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/people/shot-in-the-arm-1.754676 |archive-date = 2018-08-22 | url-status = live | access-date = 2018-08-22 }}</ref> to Noreen McElhone and Michael Taylor, both journalists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2009/nov/28/natascha-mcelhone-my-family-values|title=Natascha McElhone: my family values|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> She took her mother's maiden name as her stage name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/4/Natascha-McElhone.html|title=Natascha McElhone|work=Filmreference.com|accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> McElhone has a [[screenwriter|scriptwriter]] brother, Damon, who lives in [[Los Angeles]]; and two half-brothers: Alexander, who lives in [[Z\u00fcrich]], and Nicholas, who lives in [[Stockholm]]. Her parents separated when she was two. Her [[Irish people|Irish]] mother moved the family to [[Brighton]] and later married journalist and columnist [[Roy Greenslade]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/greenslade/2007/03/comedy_role_for_xfiles_star_du.html|work=The Guardian|location=London, UK|title=Comedy role for X-Files star Duchovny | first=Roy | last=Greenslade | date=15 March 2007|accessdate=19 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nMcElhone, who took lessons in [[Irish dancing]] from ages 6\u201312, was educated at St. Mark's CofE Primary School, Brighton, [[St Mary's Hall, Brighton|St. Mary's Hall]] School for Girls, an independent [[boarding school]] in [[Brighton]], [[Sussex]], Fortismere School, London, Camden School for Girls, London and William Ellis, London. She graduated from the [[London Academy of Music and Dramatic Art]] in 1993.<ref name=\"Natascha\">{{cite web|title=Natascha McElhone- Biography|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/person/natascha-mcelhone/biography.html|work=[[Yahoo! Movies]]|accessdate=11 May 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727233827/https://movies.yahoo.com/person/natascha-mcelhone/biography.html|archive-date=27 July 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMcElhone began her career in the theatre, including starring roles in ''[[Richard III (play)|Richard III]]'' and ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream]]'' at the [[Open Air Theatre, Regent's Park]], London, and in ''[[The Count of Monte Cristo]]'' and ''[[The Cherry Orchard]]'' at the [[Haymarket Theatre (Leicester)|Haymarket Theatre]], [[Leicester]]. She made her television debut in the [[BBC]]'s ''[[Bergerac (TV series)|Bergerac]]'' in 1991 (credited on screen as Natascha Taylor), and was seen in an episode of ''[[Absolutely Fabulous]]'' in 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/shows/absolutely-fabulous/cast/|title=Absolutely Fabulous Guest Stars|publisher=[[TV.com]]|accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Natascha McElhone (13034107645) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|McElhone at the [[Southbank Centre]], London in 2014]]\nMcElhone was seen in two episodes of the [[Dennis Potter]] TV miniseries ''[[Karaoke (play)|Karaoke]]''. Her first major box-office role came in 1996 with ''[[Surviving Picasso]]'', with co-star [[Anthony Hopkins]]. One of her most successful films to date has been 1998's ''[[The Truman Show]]'' with [[Jim Carrey]]. She had leading roles opposite [[Brad Pitt]] in ''[[The Devil's Own]]'', [[Robert De Niro]] in ''[[Ronin (film)|Ronin]]'', and [[George Clooney]] in ''[[Solaris (2002 film)|Solaris]]''.<ref name=\"Natascha\"/>\n\nIn 2005, she co-starred in the [[NBC]] miniseries ''[[Revelations (2005 TV series)|Revelations]]'' with [[Bill Pullman]]. She starred in a 2006 West End production of ''Honour'' at the [[Wyndham's Theatre]] alongside [[Diana Rigg]] and [[Martin Jarvis (actor)|Martin Jarvis]]. She then accepted a leading role in the Showtime cable television series ''[[Californication (TV series)|Californication]]'' as Karen, alongside [[David Duchovny]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/interview-natascha-mcelhone-on-becoming-a-writer-1-3475127|title=Interview: Natascha McElhone on becoming a writer|website=www.scotsman.com}}</ref> In 2009 McElhone became a spokeswoman for [[Neutrogena]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Clott|first=Sharon|title=Neutrogena Casts Natascha McElhone; Valentino Does \u2018Fearless\u2019 Eyes|url=https://nymag.com/thecut/2009/01/neutrogena_casts_natascha_mcel.html|publisher=NY Mag|accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> In 2010, she was the voice of Marie in the video game ''[[Castlevania: Lords of Shadow]]'' from [[Konami]].<ref name=\"cv\">{{cite news|title=Konami Announces Castlevania: Lords Of Shadow is Now Available|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2010/10/05/konami-announces-castlevania-lords-of-shadow-is-now-available|accessdate=11 May 2013|newspaper=IGN|date=5 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nMcElhone co-starred in a 2013 [[Romeo and Juliet (2013 film)|adaptation]] of ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]'' as Juliet's mother, [[Lady Capulet]], alongside [[Hailee Steinfeld]] and [[Damian Lewis]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Fernandez|first=Jay A.|title='Homeland' Star Damian Lewis Cast in 'Romeo and Juliet' (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/risky-business/homeland-star-damian-lewis-cast-286523|accessdate=11 May 2013|newspaper=Hollywood Reporter|date=1 February 2012}}</ref> In 2014, she played the role of Alex Forrest in ''[[Fatal Attraction (play)|Fatal Attraction]]'', at the [[Theatre Royal Haymarket]]. In 2015, McElhone starred as [[Sarah Churchill, Duchess of Marlborough|Sarah Churchill]] in the [[Royal Shakespeare Company|Royal Shakespeare Company's]] production of [[Helen Edmundson|Helen Edmundson's]] ''[[Queen Anne (play)|Queen Anne]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsc.org.uk/queen-anne/cast-and-creative |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-11-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151202055919/http://www.rsc.org.uk/queen-anne/cast-and-creative |archivedate=2 December 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, she was cast alongside [[Kiefer Sutherland]] in [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s political drama ''[[Designated Survivor (TV series)|Designated Survivor]]'', which premiered in September 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|title=\u2018Designated Survivor\u2019 Casts Kal Penn, Maggie Q, Natascha McElhone, Italia Ricci|url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/kal-penn-maggie-q-natascha-mcelhone-italia-ricci-cast-designated-survivor-abc-1201696876/|website=Deadline|accessdate=22 September 2016|date=5 February 2016}}</ref>. She left the show in Season 2 to take a role in the Hulu series ''[[The First (TV series)|The First]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nMcElhone married [[Plastic surgery|plastic surgeon]] Martin Hirigoyen Kelly{{where|date=July 2019}} on 19 May 1998.{{cn|date=July 2019}} The couple lived in [[Fulham]], West London, with their sons Theodore (born 2000) and Otis (born May 2003); their third son, Rex, was born in October 2008, five months after Kelly's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebrity-babies.com/2008/10/natascha-mcelho.html|title=Natascha McElhone Welcomes Third Child|accessdate=8 January 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081209003530/http://www.celebrity-babies.com/2008/10/natascha-mcelho.html|archive-date=9 December 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 May 2008, 43-year-old Kelly was found slumped in the doorway of his family's home by a fellow doctor, who had him rushed to [[Chelsea and Westminster Hospital]] (where he worked). However, he could not be revived. He died one day after his 10th wedding anniversary. A [[autopsy|postmortem exam]] revealed the cause of death to have been [[dilated cardiomyopathy]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article3975839.ece|title=Natascha McElhone's plastic surgeon husband dies at couple's home|work=The Times |location=UK |date=21 May 2008|accessdate=21 May 2008 | first=Jenny | last=Booth}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Watts |first1=Geoff |title=Obituary: Martin Hirigoyen Kelly |journal=The Lancet |date=July 2008 |volume=372 |issue=9632 |pages=24 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(08)60979-4}} {{open access}}</ref>\n\nAfter her husband's sudden death, McElhone continued to write letters to him, sometimes documenting the daily trivia of life but also dealing with how she and their young children were [[coping (psychology)|coping]] with their loss. These letters and diary entries formed the basis of her book ''After You: Letters of Love, and Loss, to a Husband and Father''. The book was published in July 2010 (the book is titled ''After You'' in the UK [[Amazon Kindle|Kindle]] version only).<ref>{{cite news|last=Day|first=Elizabeth|title=After You: Letters of Love, and Loss, to a Husband and Father by Natascha McElhone|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2010/jul/04/after-you-natascha-mcelhone|accessdate=11 May 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=3 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = McElhone | first = Natascha | title = After you: letters of love, and loss, to a husband and father | publisher = Viking | location = London | year = 2010 | isbn = 9780670919093 }}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|+ List of film wo